"""
MKT Context Commentary — Numbers chapters 8–10
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-numbers-8-10.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/numbers.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/numbers.json (MKT text)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch 8: Levite consecration uses vocabulary of animal sacrifice applied to persons;
  age-brackets (25-50) reconciled with Num 4 (30-50) as apprenticeship period
- Ch 9: The Passover section is chronologically prior to ch 1 (1st month vs. 2nd month,
  same year) — deliberate anachronism for thematic ordering
- Ch 9: The guiding cloud section (v15-23) uses shakan (dwell) root throughout — connects
  to mishkan (tabernacle); cloud = Shekinah presence
- Ch 10: Chatsotsrot (silver trumpets) are distinct from the shofar; four distinct signals
- Ch 10: Inverted nuns (Nun hafukhah) bracket vv35-36 in the Hebrew text — ancient
  scribal markers indicating a separate literary unit
- Ch 10: Hobab's identity as father-in-law is debated (cf. Num 10:29 Raguel/Reuel
  vs. Exod 3:1 Jethro); most scholars identify Hobab as Moses's brother-in-law
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>This brief instruction opens a narrative unit (vv1-4) addressing the lampstand (<em>menorah</em>). The placement here — after the tabernacle's completion and the tribal offerings of ch 7 — reflects the need to clarify the orientation of the lamps before Israel departs Sinai. The lamp-setting command appears in a cluster of priestly-service instructions (chs. 6-10) that flesh out the operational details of Israel's worship while encamped.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The instruction &ldquo;when you set up the lamps&rdquo; uses <em>beha'alotecha</em> (when you cause them to go up) — the Hebrew title of this section of Numbers. The phrase clarifies that the seven lamps of the golden lampstand (<em>menorah</em>) are to be arranged so that they illuminate the space directly in front of the lampstand, i.e., the table of showbread on the north side of the holy place. The lampstand stood on the south side; the lamps facing forward cast light toward the north across the holy space, symbolizing YHWH's light illuminating the covenant meal.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Aaron's obedience is noted explicitly — &ldquo;as the LORD had commanded Moses.&rdquo; The lamp-setting formula here echoes the Sinai compliance formulas of Exodus (Exod 39-40), where each element of the tabernacle construction is confirmed as done &ldquo;as YHWH commanded Moses.&rdquo; Aaron's faithful service as the ordained lamp-lighter is a foundational priestly duty; it continues daily throughout the tabernacle and temple period.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The lampstand was of hammered work (<em>miqshah</em>), beaten out of a single piece of gold from its base to its flowering tops — no joints or seams. The original specification appears in Exod 25:31-40 with the same technical term. <em>Miqshah</em> (from <em>qashah</em>, to be hard) indicates hammered or wrought work rather than cast work. The mention here that Moses made it &ldquo;according to the pattern YHWH had shown him&rdquo; (Exod 25:40) confirms the lampstand as a heavenly archetype rendered in earthly materials — a theme Hebrews later exploits.</p>",
    "5": "<p>A new instruction section begins: the consecration of the Levites. This unit (vv5-26) is the formal initiation ceremony for the Levites as a distinct cultic class, analogous to but deliberately different from the priestly ordination of Aaron and his sons in Lev 8-9. The Levites assist the priests; they are consecrated but not ordained; they perform physical tabernacle service but do not approach the altar or enter the holy place.</p>",
    "6": "<p>&ldquo;Take the Levites from among the Israelites and cleanse them&rdquo; — the Levites are to be <em>separated</em> from the larger community and <em>purified</em> before service. Two verbs: <em>laqach</em> (take/set apart) and <em>tiharta</em> (cleanse, from <em>taher</em>). The structure mirrors the separation of the holy from the common that characterizes all Levitical thought: what is set apart for YHWH must be ritually clean. The Levites stand between Israel and the holy service, absorbing impurity on Israel's behalf (v19).</p>",
    "7": "<p>The cleansing procedure for Levites involves three elements: (1) sprinkling with <em>mei chattat</em> (purification water, literally &ldquo;sin water&rdquo;), (2) shaving all their hair, and (3) washing their clothes. The purification water used here anticipates the fuller description of the red heifer water in ch 19. Hair-shaving removes a physical boundary-marker of the old life; washing clothes (used at Sinai itself, Exod 19:10) is standard preparation for encountering the holy. The combination of water, shaving, and washing is a comprehensive bodily purification.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Two bulls are required: one for a <em>chatat</em> (sin offering) and one for a <em>olah</em> (burnt offering), along with a grain offering (<em>minchah</em>) of fine flour mixed with oil. The same pairing — sin offering plus burnt offering — appears at priestly ordination (Lev 8-9) and at major transition ceremonies. The sin offering addresses the Levites' own ritual impurity; the burnt offering signals total consecration to YHWH. The grain offering accompanies the burnt offering as standard practice (Lev 2).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The assembly of the whole congregation as witnesses to the Levite consecration gives the ceremony communal weight. The Levites do not receive their commission privately; the entire community of Israel (represented by its assembly) is present, signifying that the Levites serve on behalf of the community and that Israel collectively acknowledges their appointment. This public commissioning parallels the NT pattern of ordination before the congregation (1 Tim 4:14).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The most striking element: the Israelites (not Aaron the priest) lay their hands on the Levites. The typical direction of hand-laying is the one being consecrated placing hands on the animal; here the community places hands on persons. Hand-laying (<em>samach</em>) in this context transfers representative status — just as the worshiper identifies with the sacrificial animal by placing hands on it, Israel identifies the Levites as their representatives before YHWH. The Levites become Israel's living wave-offering to God.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Aaron &ldquo;presents&rdquo; (<em>henif</em>, waves) the Levites as a <em>tenufah</em> (wave offering) before YHWH. The wave offering gesture involves moving the gift toward the altar (toward YHWH) and back — a symbolic giving and receiving. Applying this term to human beings is unusual; the Levites are treated analogously to a dedicated gift offered to and received from YHWH for his service. The phrase &ldquo;from the Israelites, so that they may do the work of the LORD&rdquo; grounds the Levites' service in their representative function for the whole nation.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Levites now perform the normal sacrifice gesture: they lay their hands on the heads of the two bulls. In doing so they identify the bulls as their own substitutionary offerings — the bulls' death on the altar is the Levites' symbolic death-and-consecration. The pattern mirrors individual sacrifice: the worshiper lays hands on the animal, confessing that this death is theirs; the animal dies in their place; they are cleansed. Here the entire Levitical order undergoes this corporate substitutionary consecration.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The Levites are stationed (<em>amdeta</em>, caused to stand) before Aaron and his sons. The verb <em>amad</em> (stand) in priestly texts consistently denotes readiness for service and subordination in the hierarchy. The Levites stand before the priests as those who serve under priestly supervision, not as equal officers. This hierarchical arrangement — YHWH → Aaron → Levites → Israel — is the structure governing all tabernacle service throughout Numbers.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;In this way you shall set the Levites apart from the Israelites, and the Levites shall be mine.&rdquo; The possessive &ldquo;mine&rdquo; (<em>li</em>) is the key theological statement: the Levites belong to YHWH in a special sense that distinguishes them from ordinary Israelites. Separation (<em>hivdaltem</em>, from <em>badal</em>, the same root used for separating holy from unholy in Lev 10:10) marks the Levites as a distinct category between priest and layperson in Israel's cultic structure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The timing formula: &ldquo;after this&rdquo; — after purification and presentation — the Levites enter service. The purification precedes the work; the cleansing makes the service possible. This order (purification → consecration → service) is structurally identical to the priestly ordination sequence in Lev 8 and to the baptism-then-ministry pattern that the NT takes up. Service without prior cleansing is dangerous (cf. Num 4:15, 20 where unauthorized approach to the holy means death).</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;For they are wholly given to me from among the Israelites&rdquo; — the double emphasis (<em>netunin netunin</em>, fully given, an intensifying repetition) marks the unconditional nature of the Levites' dedication to YHWH. They have been taken (<em>laqachti</em>) by YHWH himself, not merely volunteered. This language anticipates the Johannine notion of those whom the Father has &ldquo;given&rdquo; to the Son — the logic of divine claim and human dedication runs through both covenants.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;For every firstborn among the Israelites is mine, both human and animal.&rdquo; YHWH grounds the Levites' special status in his claim on firstborns, established at the Exodus (Exod 13:2, 12-15). When YHWH struck the firstborns of Egypt and spared Israel's, he established a permanent claim: every firstborn male in Israel belongs to YHWH and must be redeemed. The Levites are the structural solution to this mass-dedication: rather than requiring every Israelite household to present its firstborn for tabernacle service, YHWH accepts the entire Levitical tribe as the collective substitute.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The exchange is explicit: &ldquo;I have taken the Levites in place of all the firstborn among the Israelites.&rdquo; <em>Tachat</em> (in place of, substituting for) is the OT's standard term for substitution. The Levites' service is vicarious — they serve in the place of others. Their dedication releases the firstborns of the other tribes from their own obligation to YHWH, though the monetary redemption of firstborns remained in force (Num 3:46-51). The substitutionary logic embedded here in Israel's tribal structure is part of the Pentateuch's broader theology of representation and vicarious service.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The Levites are given as a <em>matanah</em> (gift) to Aaron and his sons, but their ultimate purpose is stated as &ldquo;to serve on behalf of the Israelites at the tent of meeting and to make atonement for the Israelites.&rdquo; The atonement function (<em>lechapper</em>, from <em>kaphar</em>) is surprising — the Levites' role in maintaining tabernacle access and managing the holy objects forms a protective buffer: when Israel draws near the sanctuary without proper mediation, &ldquo;there will be a plague among the Israelites.&rdquo; The Levites' service is thus protective, absorbing the danger of Israel's proximity to the holy.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The execution notice: Moses, Aaron, and all the community of Israel did as YHWH commanded regarding the Levites. The triple compliance formula (Moses + Aaron + all Israel) appears at key moments of covenant-establishment and marks this as a foundational, community-wide act. It is not a private priestly arrangement but Israel as a whole acknowledging the Levitical order.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;The Levites purified themselves and washed their clothes. Aaron presented them as a wave offering before the LORD, and Aaron made atonement for them to cleanse them.&rdquo; The Levites actively participate in their own purification: the cleansing is not done to them alone but requires their own acts (<em>vayitchatte'u</em>, they purified/de-sinned themselves). Aaron's waving and atonement-making is then confirmed with the sacrifice of the bulls at the altar. The sequence makes the Levites' consecration legally complete.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Levites begin service after — and only after — the full consecration ceremony is completed. Numbers is careful to establish that proper procedure precedes access to the holy; premature approach to the sanctuary is lethal (Num 4:15, 18-20). The phrase &ldquo;before Aaron and his sons&rdquo; reaffirms the subordinate relationship: the Levites work under priestly authority and within priestly supervision, not independently.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Another divine-speech formula marks a new subsection: the Levite age regulations (vv23-26). This instruction is distinct from the age regulations of ch 4 (which set the age bracket for Kohathite, Gershonite, and Merarite carrying service at 30-50 years). The numbers may represent different roles: ch 4 gives the age for the demanding physical carrying service during the wilderness march; ch 8 may represent a lower age for entering apprentice-level tabernacle service.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;From twenty-five years old and upward they shall enter to serve in the work (<em>avodat tzava</em>, the military-service of service) at the tent of meeting.&rdquo; The term <em>tzava</em> (service, military service) is used for Levitical work throughout Numbers 1-4, framing the Levites' tabernacle duties as a form of sacred military service. The phrase &ldquo;enter to do service&rdquo; (<em>lavo livot avodah</em>) likely describes initial entry into a training period before taking on the full carrying burdens of ch 4's 30-50 bracket. The five years between 25 and 30 may be an apprenticeship under senior Levites.</p>",
    "25": "<p>&ldquo;And from age fifty they shall retire from the service work and serve no longer.&rdquo; <em>Yashov me'tzeva ha'avodah</em> (retire from the warfare of service) — the same military imagery used for entering service now frames leaving it. Fifty marks the end of active carrying duty, likely because the physical demands of transporting the heavy tabernacle components across the wilderness were significant. The Levitical service has a natural life-cycle: preparation (25-30?), full service (30-50), and honorable retirement.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Retired Levites (those over 50) may still assist their younger colleagues as helpers (<em>leshareit</em>, to minister/serve) but may not perform the principal service work. This provision preserves the dignity and contribution of elder Levites while acknowledging physical limitations. The phrase &ldquo;you shall do thus to the Levites in their offices&rdquo; (<em>bemishmarotam</em>, in their posts/watches) formalizes this as a permanent structural arrangement for Levitical service, not a temporary wilderness provision.</p>"
  },
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>Numbers 9:1 is set in &ldquo;the first month of the second year after they had come out of Egypt&rdquo; — the same year as the book's opening, but in the month before it (Num 1:1 is the second month). This is a deliberate anachronism: the narrative places the Passover account before the census because thematically the Passover renewal takes precedence. The Passover in the wilderness of Sinai is the first Passover after the original Passover in Egypt (Exod 12), making it the first anniversary celebration of the Exodus.</p>",
    "2": "<p>&ldquo;Let the Israelites keep the Passover (<em>ha-Pesach</em>) at its appointed time (<em>bemo'ado</em>).&rdquo; The use of <em>mo'ed</em> (appointed time/season) connects Passover to the full calendar of sacred times in Lev 23. The Passover is not merely a commemorative meal but an appointment with YHWH — a fixed moment in the liturgical year when Israel re-enacts its birth as a people through the redemption from Egypt. Keeping it &ldquo;at its appointed time&rdquo; is both a temporal and a covenantal obligation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The technical details: 14th of the first month (<em>Nisan</em>), at twilight (<em>bein ha-arbayim</em>, between the evenings — sunset). &ldquo;According to all its statutes and all its ordinances you shall keep it&rdquo; — the full Passover protocol of Exod 12 remains in force (unleavened bread, bitter herbs, no bone broken, eaten in haste). The command to observe it &ldquo;exactly&rdquo; in the wilderness setting demonstrates that the Passover observance is not tied to the land of Egypt but travels with Israel as a permanent covenant institution.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Moses simply transmits the command to the Israelites. The brevity here contrasts with the extended dialogue in vv6-14 about exceptional cases. The narrative moves quickly from command to complication, suggesting that the standard observance was unproblematic but that a pastoral case required new revelation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The Israelites' obedience is noted in the same terms as vv2-3: &ldquo;in the wilderness of Sinai... at the LORD's command through Moses, exactly so.&rdquo; The wilderness context is significant: Passover is kept not in the land but in the desert, confirming that Israel's covenant meal with YHWH transcends geographical location. The phrase &ldquo;just so they did&rdquo; (<em>kachol asher tsivah YHWH et-Moshe</em>) closes the compliance notice and opens the problem of the unclean men.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The case: men who were ritually unclean because of contact with a human corpse (<em>nefesh adam</em>, a human being's soul/life, a common OT idiom for a corpse). Corpse-impurity was one of the most severe forms of ritual impurity in Levitical law (Num 19:11-22 gives the full purification procedure), requiring a seven-day waiting period. These men were excluded from participating in the Passover on its proper day through no apparent moral failure — a circumstance the Mosaic law had not yet addressed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The men's complaint is theologically important: &ldquo;Why should we be excluded from bringing the LORD's offering at its appointed time among the Israelites?&rdquo; They are not refusing to participate — they want to participate but are unable. Their exclusion is not due to unbelief or rebellion but to unavoidable circumstance (contact with a corpse was often required by duty, e.g., burying a relative). Their question presents a genuine pastoral dilemma: does ritual impurity permanently exclude sincere worshipers from covenant participation?</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;Moses said to them, Wait here, and I will hear what the LORD commands about you.&rdquo; This is a model of how to handle unprecedented cases in Mosaic law: Moses neither improvises an answer nor refuses to engage; he takes the case to YHWH. This procedure — bringing difficult cases to YHWH for direct revelation — appears also in the daughters of Zelophehad's inheritance case (Num 27:5) and models the principle that the law can be extended through properly mediated divine counsel to cover unanticipated situations.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The formula <em>vayedabber YHWH el-Moshe lemor</em> (YHWH spoke to Moses saying) marks a new divine speech in response to the question. The narrative pattern — human problem → Moses brings it to YHWH → YHWH speaks → resolution — is a recurring structure in Numbers that demonstrates YHWH's ongoing involvement in Israel's practical life, not just in the giving of the foundational law at Sinai.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The make-up Passover provision: anyone unclean because of a corpse or on a long journey may delay Passover observance to the 14th of the second month (<em>Iyar</em>). This &ldquo;Second Passover&rdquo; (<em>Pesach Sheni</em>) became a recognized institution in later Jewish practice. The explicit inclusion of the &ldquo;distant road&rdquo; case (<em>bederech rechokah</em>) shows that physical distance, not just ritual impurity, is a legitimate reason for delay. Neither circumstance excuses permanent abstention; only temporary deferral is permitted.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The Second Passover follows exactly the same rules as the First: 14th of the second month, at twilight, with unleavened bread and bitter herbs. The same time formula (<em>bein ha-arbayim</em>) and the same foods apply. The make-up provision does not create a lesser Passover but a full covenant meal on a different date — YHWH's accommodation to human circumstances without diminishing the content of the celebration.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;They shall leave none of it until morning and shall not break any of its bones&rdquo; — the same two rules applied to the original Passover in Exod 12:10, 46. &ldquo;They shall observe it according to all the statute of the Passover.&rdquo; The &ldquo;no broken bones&rdquo; rule (Exod 12:46; Num 9:12) was applied to Jesus's crucifixion in John 19:36 (&ldquo;these things took place that the Scripture might be fulfilled: not one of his bones will be broken&rdquo;), making this verse directly messianic in its NT application. The intactness of the Passover lamb's bones is the type of the incorruption of the true Passover sacrifice.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The warning against deliberate neglect is severe: one who is clean, not on a journey, and yet fails to keep the Passover shall be &ldquo;cut off from his people&rdquo; (<em>venichreta hanefesh hahi me'ammeha</em>, the classic formula for <em>karet</em>) and &ldquo;shall bear his sin.&rdquo; <em>Karet</em> (cutting off) may mean premature death, exclusion from the covenant community, or both. The contrast between the accommodated cases (vv10-12) and this deliberate neglect (v13) is sharp: YHWH provides for the genuinely hindered but has no patience for willful abstention from covenant participation.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The alien (<em>ger</em>) resident may keep the Passover under the same rules as native Israelites — &ldquo;there shall be one statute for you, both for the stranger and for the native.&rdquo; This inclusion of foreigners in Passover is significant: the festival that defines Israel as YHWH's redeemed people is not racially exclusive. Gentile conversion to Israel's God included participation in the covenant meal. The principle of one law for alien and native (also in Lev 24:22; Num 15:16) is a foundational element of OT universalism that the NT develops more fully.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The cloud-and-fire narrative (vv15-23) begins here. &ldquo;On the day the tabernacle was set up&rdquo; — the narrative returns to the moment of Exod 40:34-38 when the cloud covered the tent and YHWH's glory filled it. The cloud (<em>anan</em>) covered the tabernacle (<em>mishkan ha'edut</em>, the tabernacle of the covenant/testimony) by day; at night it had the appearance of fire. The cloud is YHWH's visible presence with Israel — not a meteorological phenomenon but a theophanic symbol.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;This was the regular pattern&rdquo; — the phrase establishes the cloud as Israel's permanent guide throughout the wilderness period. <em>Ken yihyeh tamid</em> (thus it was always/continuously) signals ongoing, uninterrupted divine guidance. The visibility of YHWH's presence made Israel's navigation entirely God-directed: no human scout, general, or leader determined the route; the cloud alone set the itinerary.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The cloud's movement directly governed Israel's movement: &ldquo;Wherever the cloud settled, there the Israelites camped.&rdquo; The verb <em>shakan</em> (settled/dwelt) for the cloud's resting shares a root with <em>mishkan</em> (tabernacle) and <em>Shekinah</em> — YHWH's dwelling-presence. When the cloud &ldquo;dwelt&rdquo; in a location, Israel also &ldquo;dwelt&rdquo; there. The tabernacle was always at the center of the camp when Israel stopped; YHWH's resting place determined Israel's resting place. The cloud-and-camp connection embodies the theological principle that where God dwells, his people dwell.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;At the LORD's command the Israelites set out, and at the LORD's command they camped.&rdquo; The phrase <em>al-pi YHWH</em> (at the mouth/command of YHWH) appears seven times in vv18-23 — a deliberate rhetorical pattern emphasizing total divine sovereignty over Israel's movements. Seven occurrences of &ldquo;at YHWH's command&rdquo; structure the entire cloud section as a meditation on obedience: whether Israel moved or stopped was never their own decision. The wilderness period is thus a training ground for radical dependence on divine direction.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Long stays required sustained obedience: &ldquo;When the cloud remained over the tabernacle for many days, the Israelites kept the LORD's charge and did not set out.&rdquo; <em>Vayishmeru bnei Yisrael et-mishmereth YHWH velo nasa'u</em> (the Israelites kept YHWH's charge and did not journey). The temptation to move on — especially in a harsh wilderness setting — would have been real, but Israel remained stationary as long as the cloud did. This tests the patience and trust of the community.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The pattern holds whether stays are long or short: &ldquo;Sometimes the cloud remained over the tabernacle for only a few days; at the LORD's command they remained and at the LORD's command they set out.&rdquo; Short encampments test a different kind of obedience — not patience in waiting but readiness to move quickly. YHWH's timing is neither predictable nor convenient; it requires a community always prepared both to stay and to go.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;Sometimes the cloud remained only from evening until morning; when the cloud lifted in the morning, they set out.&rdquo; A single-night encampment followed by immediate departure — Israel would have barely unpacked before the cloud moved. The text accepts without complaint that YHWH's command might require an overnight stop and an early-morning departure. The same pattern by day or night: the cloud's movement is authoritative regardless of time or convenience.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The comprehensive summary: &ldquo;Whether the cloud remained for two days, a month, or a year over the tabernacle, the Israelites stayed in camp and did not set out; but when it lifted, they set out.&rdquo; The three time durations (days, month, year) form a literary escalation covering the full range of possible stays. The point is exhaustive: there was no duration too short or too long that would justify Israel moving independently of the cloud. YHWH's guidance was total and Israel's submission was expected to be total.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The closing summary of the cloud section: &ldquo;At the LORD's command they camped, and at the LORD's command they set out. They kept the LORD's charge, at the LORD's command through Moses.&rdquo; The final <em>al-pi YHWH beyad-Moshe</em> (at YHWH's command through Moses's hand) reaffirms the mediation structure: YHWH speaks through Moses, and Moses conveys the commands that the cloud visually signals. The visible cloud and the verbal instruction through Moses are the two channels of divine guidance working in concert.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>A new divine speech opens the silver trumpet section (vv1-10). The trumpets are a distinct topic from the cloud-guidance of ch 9 but complement it: the cloud signals YHWH's movement; the trumpets signal how Israel coordinates its response. Together they represent the two modes of divine-human communication in the wilderness march — visual revelation and oral/auditory command.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Two silver trumpets (<em>chatsotsrot</em>) made of hammered silver (<em>miqshah</em>, the same workmanship as the lampstand in v4 above). <em>Chatsotsrot</em> are straight metal trumpets, distinct from the curved ram's horn (<em>shofar</em>). The two trumpets together can produce different signal-patterns: both blown together, one blown alone, alarm blasts, or sustained notes. Their dual nature allows four distinct signals for four distinct purposes (vv3-10), creating an elaborate communication system for Israel's large community.</p>",
    "3": "<p>&ldquo;When both are blown, the whole assembly shall gather to you at the entrance of the tent of meeting.&rdquo; Both trumpets blown = full community assembly. The tent of meeting entrance is the designated assembly point — the center of the camp, the place of divine encounter. The community is summoned to YHWH's dwelling place for corporate action, not merely to Moses's location. The trumpet system reinforces the tabernacle's central place in Israel's communal life.</p>",
    "4": "<p>One trumpet blown = leaders only (<em>hanesiyim rashei alfei Yisrael</em>, the chiefs, heads of Israel's thousands). The graduated signal system reflects the tiered leadership structure of Israel: full assembly requires a full signal; a leadership council requires a partial signal. This practical distinction prevents the disruption of the whole camp for matters that only the leadership needs to address, while still maintaining a clear auditory protocol.</p>",
    "5": "<p>&ldquo;When you blow an alarm (<em>teruah</em>), the camps on the east side shall set out.&rdquo; <em>Teruah</em> is a broken, staccato blast (as opposed to the long sustained note <em>tekiah</em>). The directional march order — east first, then south — corresponds to the encampment and march order described in Num 2. The silver trumpet system thus operationalizes the tribal camping order of the census: the trumpet translates YHWH's structural command into auditory action for a large group that can't all see the ark's movement simultaneously.</p>",
    "6": "<p>A second alarm signals the southern camps to set out. The text notes: &ldquo;An alarm shall be blown for their setting out&rdquo; — a general principle that the alarm blast is always the march signal for each camp division. The west (Ephraim) and north (Dan) camps presumably set out on third and fourth alarms, though the text doesn't enumerate them; the pattern is established by the first two. The consistent alarm system gives the whole community (possibly numbering in the hundreds of thousands) an auditory coordination signal audible across the camp.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;But when the assembly is to be gathered, you shall blow without an alarm call.&rdquo; Assembly uses the sustained <em>tekiah</em> (a long, steady note), not the staccato <em>teruah</em> (march alarm). This distinction prevents confusion between &ldquo;gather&rdquo; and &ldquo;march&rdquo; signals. The two uses of the trumpet — assembly and march — represent the two modes of community life: gathering for worship and decision, and dispersing for movement and battle. The trumpet system orchestrates both.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;The priests, the sons of Aaron, shall blow the trumpets. This shall be a permanent statute throughout your generations.&rdquo; The trumpets are priestly instruments, not military ones. Their use belongs to the priestly order and is a &ldquo;permanent statute&rdquo; (<em>chuqqat olam</em>), meaning it persists beyond the wilderness. Later temple practice involved priestly trumpeters (1 Chron 15:24; 16:6; 2 Chron 5:12-13), confirming that the silver trumpet remained a priestly instrument in the cultus. The term <em>chuqqat olam</em> (perpetual statute) places this beside other permanent Levitical ordinances.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;When you go to war in your land against an enemy who attacks you, sound an alarm with the trumpets. Then you will be remembered before the LORD your God and saved from your enemies.&rdquo; The trumpet as memorial instrument before YHWH: <em>venizchartem lifnei YHWH</em> (you will be remembered before YHWH). This theology of divine &ldquo;remembrance&rdquo; (<em>zachar</em>) appears throughout the OT — when God &ldquo;remembers,&rdquo; he acts to fulfill his covenant commitments. The trumpet blast in battle is not magic but a covenant-appeal: &ldquo;YHWH, we are your people; remember your promises and deliver us.&rdquo;</p>",
    "10": "<p>The festive use of trumpets: &ldquo;On your joyful days — your appointed festivals (<em>moadeichem</em>) and the beginnings of your months (<em>rashei chodsheichem</em>) — you shall blow the trumpets over your burnt offerings and your peace offerings.&rdquo; The same instrument signals both war and worship; it belongs equally to sacred assembly and battle cry. The monthly new moon (<em>rosh chodesh</em>) trumpet blast became one of the major Levitical calendar practices, persisting into the Second Temple period. The phrase &ldquo;a memorial before your God&rdquo; frames all trumpet use — war or festival — as covenant remembrance before YHWH.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The departure date: 20th of the second month of the second year. Israel arrived at Sinai in the third month of the first year after the Exodus (Exod 19:1). They depart in the second month of year two. The stay at Sinai was approximately eleven months — a period during which the entire Mosaic law was given (Exod 19 – Num 10:11), the tabernacle was built and consecrated, the first census was taken, the Levitical service orders were established, and the cloud-guidance system was explained. Sinai is not a stop on the journey but Israel's formative school.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The Israelites set out &ldquo;from the wilderness of Sinai, stage by stage&rdquo; (<em>lemas'eihem</em>, literally, according to their journeyings/stages). The cloud comes to rest in the wilderness of Paran — an identified region northeast of Sinai and south of Canaan. This is the first forward movement after the long Sinai encampment. The wilderness of Paran will later be the staging area for the spy mission (Num 12:16; 13:3), where the generation's faith collapses.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;They set out for the first time at the LORD's command through Moses.&rdquo; The note &ldquo;for the first time&rdquo; (<em>barishonah</em>) marks this departure as inaugural — Israel's first march from its point of foundational formation. The phrase reinforces the cloud-guidance theme of ch 9: the departure is fully authorized, at YHWH's command, through Moses. No human initiative started the march; divine movement initiated it.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The march order follows the tribal camping arrangement of Num 2: Judah's standard leads as the vanguard. The commanders are named — Nahshon son of Amminadab, the same leader listed in the census (Num 1:7). The listing of specific leaders by name gives the departure an official, census-linked character: this is the registered, counted army of Israel setting out in its proper order under its appointed commanders.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Nethaneel son of Zuar, over the force of Issachar — the second tribe of the Judah-standard camp (Num 2:5-6). The names track exactly with the census and camping lists of Num 1-2, demonstrating the Pentateuch's concern for orderly, documented structure in Israel's communal life. The repetition of leader names across the census, offering, and march lists creates a coherent narrative of Israel as a governed community, not a wandering mob.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Eliab son of Helon, over the force of Zebulun — the third tribe of the Judah-standard camp (Num 2:7). Zebulun completes the first of four camp-divisions in the march. The three-tribe groupings under each standard reflect the organizational principle of Num 2: each standard anchors three tribes in a quadrant of the camp. On the march, this becomes three tribes advancing in column under their standard.</p>",
    "17": "<p>After the Judah-standard's three tribes, the tabernacle itself is disassembled and carried. &ldquo;The tabernacle was taken down, and the sons of Gershon and the sons of Merari set out, carrying the tabernacle.&rdquo; In Num 4, Gershon carries the fabric components (curtains, coverings, screens) and Merari carries the structural components (frames, bars, pillars, bases). They march after Judah's camp but before Reuben's, so that by the time Reuben's camp arrives at a new site, the tabernacle structure is ready to be erected by the Kohathites.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Reuben's standard sets out second — the southern camp (Num 2:10-16), commanded by Elizur son of Shedeur. The four-camp march order (Judah, Reuben, Ephraim, Dan) places the camps that served as vanguard and rear guard in the first and last positions, with the two middle camps flanking the central tabernacle column. The organizational sophistication of this march order reflects a military formation designed for wilderness travel with a large population and precious cargo.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shelumiel son of Zurishaddai, over the force of Simeon — the second tribe of Reuben's southern camp. The same name appears in the census (Num 1:6) and tribal offerings (Num 7:36). The consistency of leadership across Numbers' lists suggests a stable tribal administration, not a changing leadership roster.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Eliasaph son of Deuel, over the force of Gad — the third tribe of Reuben's camp. The southern camp's three tribes complete their march formation. Between Reuben's departure and Ephraim's follows the Kohathite column (v21), carrying the sanctuary items.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;The Kohathites set out, carrying the holy objects (<em>hammiqdash</em>, the sanctuary/holy things).&rdquo; The Kohathites carry the most sacred items — the ark, table, lampstand, altars, and their utensils — all wrapped and covered by the priests before the Kohathites lift them (Num 4:4-20). They follow Reuben's camp, and the text notes: &ldquo;The others would set up the tabernacle before they arrived.&rdquo; This is the Gershon and Merari groups (v17), who went ahead to erect the structural tabernacle so the Kohathites can deposit the holy objects into an already-standing structure when they arrive at the new campsite. The coordination is precise.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ephraim's standard — the western camp (Num 2:18-24) — sets out third. Elishama son of Ammihud commands it. The western camp of Ephraim, Manasseh, and Benjamin forms the third march division. Placing Ephraim (the large northern tribe of Joseph) in the third position ensures that the rear of the column is secured by the strong Dan rear guard (v25), while Ephraim's substantial numbers fill the column's third quarter.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Gamaliel son of Pedahzur, over the force of Manasseh — second tribe of Ephraim's camp. The same leader from the census and tribal offerings lists (Num 1:10; 7:54). The half-tribe of Manasseh is enumerated separately from Ephraim (both sons of Joseph, Num 1:32-35) to maintain twelve active tribal units in the census and march (Levi being the thirteenth, given a separate role).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Abidan son of Gideoni, over the force of Benjamin — the third tribe of Ephraim's camp. Benjamin, though the smallest tribe (Num 1:37: 35,400), is full represented in the march order and carries its full tribal designation. The inclusion of Benjamin in Ephraim's camp (Num 2:22) places the two Rachel tribes together — Ephraim (son of Joseph) and Benjamin (Rachel's last son) — a geographical and genealogical grouping.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Dan's standard forms the rear guard (<em>me'asseph le'chol ha-machanot</em>, the one who gathers/collects for all the camps) — the last of the four camp divisions. Dan's position as rear guard is functionally significant: the rear guard in ancient military formation protected against attacks from behind, gathered stragglers, and ensured no camp was left exposed. The phrase &ldquo;the rear guard of all the camps&rdquo; treats the march as a military operation. Ahiezer son of Ammishaddai commands the Dan vanguard; Num 2:25-31 describes Dan's camp.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Pagiel son of Ocran, over the force of Asher — second tribe of Dan's northern rear-guard camp. The Dan-Asher-Naphtali grouping (Num 2:25-31) forms the final march column, closing the tribal procession out of the Sinai wilderness. The complete march order spans the entire community in its proper, census-validated order.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Ahira son of Enan, over the force of Naphtali — the third and final tribe of Dan's camp, and thus the last tribe listed in the march order. Naphtali trails behind all other camps, closing the procession. The tribal listing ends as it began (v14 with Judah's vanguard) — the camp order perfectly mirrors the encampment layout of Num 2, just extended into a linear march.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;These were the marching orders of the Israelites by their regiments (<em>letziv'otam</em>) when they set out.&rdquo; The summary closes the march-order list and marks it as a definitive, authorized arrangement. <em>Tzav'ot</em> (regiments, military divisions, also used in &ldquo;YHWH of hosts/armies&rdquo; — <em>YHWH Tzvaot</em>) frames Israel's march as a holy military procession under divine command. The complete march description (vv14-28) is the first movement of this army from its base camp at Sinai.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Moses invites Hobab son of Raguel (= Reuel) the Midianite, Moses's father-in-law, to join Israel. There is a textual question: Exod 3:1 calls Moses's father-in-law <em>Yitro</em> (Jethro), while Num 10:29 names him as Hobab son of Raguel. The most common solution is that Raguel/Reuel is the father-in-law, and Hobab is Moses's brother-in-law (cf. Judg 4:11). Either way, Moses extends covenant hospitality: &ldquo;Come with us and we will treat you well, for the LORD has promised good things to Israel.&rdquo; The Midianite connection with Moses anticipates the later Midianite crisis (Num 25; 31).</p>",
    "30": "<p>Hobab's refusal: &ldquo;I will not go; I will return to my own land and my own people.&rdquo; The directness of his refusal is notable — he doesn't hedge or delay. Hobab's loyalty is to his own people (the Midianites of northwestern Arabia/Sinai), not to Israel. Yet the narrative doesn't close the door: Moses's counter-argument in vv31-32 is immediate and persistent. Judges 1:16 notes that &ldquo;the descendants of Hobab the Kenite, Moses's father-in-law, went up from the City of Palms with the people of Judah&rdquo; — suggesting Hobab eventually agreed, or at least some of his family did.</p>",
    "31": "<p>&ldquo;Please do not leave us, for you know how we are to camp in the wilderness, and you will serve as eyes for us.&rdquo; Moses's argument is pragmatic: Hobab is a wilderness native who knows the terrain, water sources, and route. &ldquo;You will serve as eyes for us&rdquo; (<em>vehayita lanu le'einayim</em>) — Hobab's local knowledge supplements the divine guidance of the cloud. This apparent tension (cloud guides + human guide) may reflect the practical distinction between YHWH's general directional leading and the practical navigation details a local guide would provide on the ground.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Moses offers reciprocal blessing: &ldquo;whatever good the LORD does for us, we will share with you.&rdquo; The Hebrew is <em>vehitova YHWH imanu veheitavnu ach</em> (when YHWH does good with us, we will do good for you). This is covenant language — the mutual exchange of benefit within relationship. Moses's offer implicitly extends the Abrahamic blessing to Hobab: those who join themselves to Israel will share in the blessing YHWH gives to Israel. The Rahab and Ruth narratives develop this theme more fully.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Israel departs &ldquo;from the mountain of the LORD on a three days' journey.&rdquo; &ldquo;The mountain of the LORD&rdquo; is Sinai — its only designation by this name in the Pentateuch (elsewhere always Sinai or Horeb). The three-day journey is a recurring biblical idiom for significant travel: Exod 3:18 (three days' journey to sacrifice); Num 10:33 (three days to find a resting place); Jonah 3:3 (Nineveh was a three days' walk). &ldquo;The ark of the LORD's covenant going before them on those three days to find a resting place for them&rdquo; — the ark precedes the camp to scout divine rest rather than Hobab's human scouting (picking up the tension of v31).</p>",
    "34": "<p>&ldquo;The cloud of the LORD was over them by day when they set out from the camp.&rdquo; The cloud's movement is again noted in departure, connecting ch 10's march to the cloud-theology of ch 9. The cloud is explicitly YHWH's cloud (<em>anan YHWH</em>), not a natural weather phenomenon. Its presence &ldquo;over them&rdquo; by day signals ongoing divine protection and guidance during the march — the Shekinah presence hovering above the company as they leave Sinai.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The ark-departure prayer: <em>Qumah YHWH veyaputzu oyvecha veyanusu mesan'echa mipanecha</em> — &ldquo;Rise up, LORD! Let your enemies be scattered; let those who hate you flee before you!&rdquo; This ancient war-prayer is one of the most striking liturgical fragments in the Pentateuch. In Hebrew manuscripts (and in the later Masoretic text), this verse and v36 are bracketed by inverted nuns (<em>nun hafukhah</em>) — ancient scribal marks indicating the verses were considered a separate literary unit, possibly a distinct &ldquo;book&rdquo; (the Talmud, Shabbat 116a, identifies Num 10:35-36 as a complete book of Scripture, making Numbers actually five books — a &ldquo;Book of the Wars of the LORD&rdquo; embedded in Numbers).</p>",
    "36": "<p>&ldquo;And when it came to rest, he would say: Return, O LORD, to the countless thousands of Israel.&rdquo; The ark-rest prayer completes the liturgical pair: departure = &ldquo;Rise up, YHWH!&rdquo;; arrival/rest = &ldquo;Return, O YHWH.&rdquo; The repeated use of the verb &ldquo;return&rdquo; (<em>shuvah</em>) implies that YHWH's going out to scatter enemies is a temporary departure from the camp; his returning signals peace and settlement. &ldquo;The countless thousands of Israel&rdquo; (<em>revavot alfei Yisrael</em>) may be deliberately hyperbolical — YHWH's return is to a vast multitude whom he has gathered to himself. These two prayers bracket every march of Israel in the wilderness, framing the entire wilderness journey as a liturgical procession under divine kingship.</p>"
  }
}

